The paper deals with the development of neural networks for learning mappings between infinite-dimensional spaces, specifically in the context of partial differential equations (PDEs). This involves the use of graph networks and kernel integration, which are techniques commonly used in machine learning and computer vision (cs.CV) applications. The paper also discusses the use of nonlinear activation functions, which are a key component of neural networks used in various subfields of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper involves numerical analysis (cs.NA) in the context of solving PDEs, and the use of learned networks to generalize among different approximation methods and levels of resolution, which could be relevant to scientific computing (cs.SI).
